    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><certainty match=".." locus="name"/><orig>ομφ</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>This puzzling fragment has a lettering too carefully cut to be taken as a simple graffito, in spite of some irregularities. Morevoer, it is not quite clear whether we have here the beginning of a text.
                 If so, one might think of two readings: on one side, we might have the word <foreign xml:lang="grc">ὀμφαλός</foreign> and the inscription would be a label for a stone <foreign rend="italic">omphalos</foreign> (at least one 
                 such sculpted piece was found in the Sanctuary of Apollo). Alternatively, we might have one of the rare personal names derived from the already mentioned word or from <foreign xml:lang="grc">ὄμφαξ</foreign>, although none is 
                 up to now attested in Cyrenaica.
       </p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
